title: “I’m trying to open the MS Beauty Salon, it’s not loading properly in Firefox. How can I fix this issue?
content: If the MS Beauty Salon website (https://msbeautysalon.co.uk/ ) isn’t loading properly in Firefox, it’s usually a browser related issue rather than a problem with the salons site. Many users visit the MS Beauty Salon in luton site for booking and service details without issues so try refreshing the page or checking your internet connection first.In Firefox clearing the cache disabling extensions or updating the browser often fixes loading problems. If the issue continues you can also try opening the website in another browser to confirm that the MS Beauty Salon in luton site itself is working normally. Visit[https://msbeautysalon.co.uk/

title: How to select multiple bookmarks?
content:
Using Firefox ESR 115.30 in Windows 7 Ultimate, I routinely open multiple tabs, then, at the end of the day or session I'll bookmark them all into a new folder and close them all.

Later, I might return to that folder and choose to open say, 5 of the group. Is there a way to select all 5 (without opening any) and once I've finished selecting them, have all 5 open at once? Rather than just one at a time? So far it seems that I have to open them one by one.

title: Exiting due to channel error. & core changes post ver ~96
content:
Since around version 96 it seemed some new core changes made to how ff operates. any one care to share what the "big changes" were around that version rollout tldr?

since ver 96 ff became secondary browser. Using to test/isolate issues w/chromium (sigh). Now since ver 132 profile manager opens browser for correct profile everything looks good then 20seconds later ff crashes eorror: Exiting due to channel error

Inspiringly i see this forum is being used still so thought i would see if anyone has ideas what changes btwn ver 96/101 and 132 which may cause this new issue, maybe i can backout the changes and get back to using ff as a secondary backup again ....

IDK about anyone else but i LOOOOONG for the ole days when ff was a daily driver option on linux
